<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-106-976  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 976.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Feb 1990 v7 n2 p42(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New ways to pay for software: dynamic licensing is a recent trendthat addresses how people use software on a network.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Southerton, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Dynamic software licensing is a two-year-old innovation thatenables users anywhere on a network to use a particular softwarepackage.andP;  The number of simultaneous users of the software on thenetwork is limited by the number of licenses that were purchased.andO;The software developer can provide the customer with a password toincrease the number of licenses on the network when needed.andO;Specific advantages include a consistent user environment nomatter where users log in on the network, and licenses can beprovided for the entire environment and not just for primaryoperating system environments.andP;  UNIX workstations vendors areleading the trend to dynamic licensing.andP;  The vendors includeApollo Computer (and parent Hewlett-Packard), Digital EquipmentCorp, and Sun Microsystems.andP;  Dynamic licensing strategies ofseveral workstation and other software vendors are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LicensingSoftwareDynamic SystemsMethodsSoftware PublishersProducts.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Apollo floating licensing implementation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>